        map2.put("location_explain", "Suwon Hwaseong Fortress: A Masterpiece of Joseon ArchitectureSuwon Hwaseong Fortress, often called the \"Flower of Joseon Fortress Architecture,\" was completed in September 1796. It was built by King Jeongjo, the 22nd monarch of the Joseon Dynasty, primarily as an act of profound filial piety for his father, Crown Prince Sado.Historical Context and Political VisionKing Jeongjo relocated his father, Crown Prince Sado's grave—who had tragically died inside a rice chest after being embroiled in political feuds—from Yangju to Hwasan in Suwon, which was considered the most propitious site (myeongdang) in Joseon. The administrative center of Suwon was then moved to its current location at the foot of Paldalsan Mountain, making way for the new fortress.While filial piety was the spiritual foundation, Hwaseong was also the centerpiece of King Jeongjo's sweeping political blueprint. It was constructed to serve as the heart of a powerful new royal capital, intended to both eradicate factional politics and establish a strong, benevolent monarchy (Wangdo politics). Furthermore, it was designed to function as a vital national defense fortress protecting the capital from the south.Scientific Construction and TechnologyThe construction, which began in January 1794 and was completed in September 1796, was a testament to meticulous planning and scientific innovation.The project was guided by the Seonghwajuryak (1793), a detailed manual compiled by scholar Jeong Yak-yong (of the Gyujanggak Royal Library), who referenced both Eastern and Western technical books.New, specially designed machinery such as the Geojunggi (a type of crane) and Nongno (a pulley system) were invented and deployed to efficiently transport and stack the enormous stone blocks, dramatically reducing construction time and costs.The fortress walls adopted the oeduknaetak technique—building only the outer wall and banking the inner side with earth using the natural terrain—allowing the structure to harmonize beautifully with the landscape.Influenced by the Silhak (Practical Learning) movement, which emphasized pragmatic application of knowledge, the fortress is considered the pinnacle of Eastern fortification techniques due to its highly scientific, rational, and practical structure. It pioneered the mixed use of brick and stone, integrating the best of both Eastern and Western construction methods.Scale and PreservationThe fortress wall stretches 5,744 meters (approximately 3.57 miles) and covers an area of 130 hectares (about 321 acres). Its design is a Pyeongsanjeong—a unique form combining a flatland fortress (to the east) with a mountain fortress (spanning Paldalsan to the west). This combined form, rarely found in China or Japan, allowed it to serve both military defense and commercial functions.While some parts were damaged during the Japanese colonial period and the Korean War, the majority of the structure was repaired and restored to its original state between 1975 and 1979, based on the highly detailed Hwaseong Seongyeok Uigwe (Royal Protocol on the Construction of Hwaseong Fortress).Lasting Significance and World HeritageThe framework of the fortress remains remarkably intact:The original walls are preserved almost completely.The Suwoncheon Stream still flows through the North Water Gate (Hwahongmun).The main roads connecting the major gates (Paldalmun, Janganmun, Changnyongmun) and the temporary palace (Haenggung) still form the core road network of the modern city center.The Hwaseong Seongyeok Uigwe, published in 1801, is an unparalleled historical asset. It meticulously documented every detail of the project, including the construction plans, designs, materials, budget, wage calculations, and even the names of the mobilized workers.Suwon Hwaseong was designated a UNESCO World Cultural Heritage site in December 1997, recognized not just for its architectural brilliance but also for embodying the Eastern philosophical value of \"Hyo\" (Filial Piety). Key structures within the fortress, such as Paldalmun, Hwaseomun, Northwest Gongsimdon, and Banghwasuryujeong Pavilion, are separately designated as Korean national treasures.");
